Database Migration Procedure

Actions
Disable specific database monitoring of the affected databases or send a message for DC Ops team / Monitoring team to disable the Database monitoring from the SQL Server Instance. (If applicable)

Arrange for application Tier to be stopped.(If applicable) Refer to the application specific notes on who does this.

Disable all application jobs (if any) in the source SQL Server once they have completed running.

Disable the Application SQL Server Login in the SQL Server if it is related to only particular database. This is to ensure Middle tiers other than the application tier cannot access database and cause an error in the log.

Once all connections to the database have been closed (i.e.. no active connections into the source database)then commence the migration work. Otherwise confirm with application support that the application tier is down. You can check whether connections exist into the database via activity monitor or running the below query in a query window.
If connections are persistent and unexplained then issue the kill command or kill the session from within SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS).



SELECT 
    DB_NAME(dbid) as DBName, hostname,
    COUNT(dbid) as NumberOfConnections,
    loginame as LoginName
FROM
    master..sysprocesses
WHERE 
    dbid > 0
GROUP BY 
    dbid, loginame,hostname
go
Script out the table count of the database being migrated



CREATE TABLE #counts
(
    table_name varchar(255),
    row_count int
)
EXEC sp_MSForEachTable @command1='INSERT #counts (table_name, row_count) 
SELECT ''?'', COUNT(*) FROM ?'
SELECT table_name, row_count FROM #counts 
ORDER BY table_name, row_count DESC
DROP TABLE #counts
 

Script out all the application jobs/Maintenance Plans and server objects that needs to be migrated to target server.

For the SQL Logins, create the Clone Logins Script to run in the destination server if not covered under Pre-Work Task

Create a folder on E:\Backup\<CRQ_yyyymmdd> or the drive in with sufficient free space available

Backup of the database on Backup drive.



BACKUP DATABASE [DATABASE_NAME] TO DISK ='E:\Backup\CRQ_yyyymmdd\DATABASE_NAME.BAK'
WITH STATS=10,COMPRESSION
Offline the Source Database.

Go to Run "<Target Server>\E$\Backup\" and copy the Database backup file from Source Server to Destination Server.

Verify the Database Backup (RESTORE VERIFYONLY) (optional)

Run the RESTORE FILELISTONLY to see a list of the files that were backed up.



RESTORE FILELISTONLY FROM DISK=E:\Backup\CRQ_yyyymmdd\DATABASE_NAME.BAK'
Restore the database to the the Target SQL Server Instance on same location where other data and log files exist// or

Restore the database with the new name (As per Council Standard)/Vendor provided name and new physical file name.



RESTORE DATABASE [DATABASE_NAME]
FROM DISK=E:\Backup\CRQ_yyyymmdd\DATABASE_NAME.BAK'
WITH MOVE 'LOGICAL_NAME' TO 'PHYSICAL_LOCATION_DESTINATION,
MOVE 'LOGICAL_NAME' TO 'PHYSICAL_LOCATION_DESTINATION',
STATS=10
Alter the Logical file name of database accordingly new database Name.

Set the Auto grow size of data and log in (MB) for the database if it is not set properly. (Auto grow must be carefully evaluated)

Ensure the database owner is the same as that nominated in the source SQL server.

If you encounter any such error : The proposed new database owner is already a user or aliased in the database. Change the owner as 'sa'



use <DATABASE_NAME>
go
sp_changedbowner '<SQL Server Login>/<sa>'
go
Re-validate the Database owner name, logical file name after making all the changes.

Enable SQL Server Logins on the target SQL Database Server. If the SQL Server logins were not cloned the login id's in the source server are likely to be different to those in the target server and the database users become orphaned (disconnected from a login) after a migration. To resolve this use the system stored procedure to 're-connect' the user to a login. Orphaning can happen if the database user is mapped to a SID that is not present in the new server instance.



--To Detect orphan users
use <DATABASE_NAME>
go
exec sp_change_users_login 'Report'
go 
--To Resolve the orphan users
1.The following command relinks the server login account specified by <login_name> with the database user specified by <database_user>. 
exec sp_change_users_login 'Update_One','<SQL Server Login>','<Database User Name>'
(we typically map users and logins to the same name)
Confirm there are no physical or logical errors in database with DBCC



use <DATABASE_NAME>
go
--Use the below command to quickly identify issues. Follow instructions provided by output.
DBCC UPDATEUSAGE ('<DATABASE_NAME>')
go
Update all existing statistics with FULL sample Size.



use <DATABASE_NAME>
go
EXEC sp_updatestats
Rebuild all indexes identified from the Pre Work Activities.



USE <DATABASE_NAME>
GO
EXEC sp_MSForEachTable 'ALTER INDEX ALL ON ? REBUILD WITH (FILLFACTOR = 90);'
--If you are getting error in above command then Execute the below script 
EXEC sp_MSForEachTable  'SET QUOTED_IDENTIFIER ON;
ALTER INDEX ALL ON ? REBUILD WITH (FILLFACTOR = 90)' 
